shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stonor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Stonor (Oxon).","2  English: occasional variant of   Stoner  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stoner","meanings":["English (Sussex): topographic name from Middle English <i>ston(e)</i> ‘stone’ + <i>-er</i>, used for someone who lived by a prominent rock or stone, or perhaps who came from a place called Stone, although this formation is more rare. See   Stone   and compare   Stoneman  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Steiner  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Stonor was born about 1156, in Stonor, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son. He died about 1185, at the age of 31."},"et":{"about 1156–about 1185":"umbes 1156–umbes 1185","1183–1222":"1183–1222","1156–1185":"1156–1185","1156":"1156","1222":"1222","about 1156":"umbes 1156","1185":"